          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Summarize (Orchestrating the Discussion)</strong></p><p><em>Discussing Solutions and Strategies </em></p><p>Have students present and discuss their strategies for answering the questions. Focus the students on the equivalent ratio and unit rate relationships. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "TILEaEpukrmTiJ4E",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Suggested Questions</strong></p><p>With each strategy in the Initial Challenge, have students justify why the strategy works. Then ask students to connect how the different strategies represent the same type of thinking. </p><ul><li>Whose strategy (Brandon&#x27;s, Sofia&#x27;s, or Kaedon&#x27;s) is most like how you thought about answering the questions about the smoothie bars? </li><li>Is there one strategy you prefer over the others? Why? </li><li>How do the strategies compare?</li><li>How did you fill in your rate table for What If..? Situation A?</li><li>How is finding equivalent ratios helpful to answer questions? </li><li>How does finding the quantities on the table help you think about how to write the equation for the cost in What If..? Situation A?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
